================================
CATEGORY 1: CREATIONAL PATTERNS
================================
DEFINITION:
Creational patterns focus on the mechanisms of object creation. They aim to 
create objects in a manner suitable to the situation, providing more 
flexibility and control than standard direct instantiation (e.g., MyClass()).

CORE GOALS:
- Encapsulate the knowledge of which concrete classes the system uses.
- Hide how instances of these classes are created and put together.
- Decouple the client code from the specific "new" keyword logic.

COFFEE SHOP CONTEXT:
Imagine the process of getting a cup of coffee. You don't go into the back 
room, grab a filter, measure the grounds, and boil the water yourself. 
You use a "system" (the counter or a machine) to get the result. 
Creational patterns are the "Systems" that handle the "How" and "When" 
of making the coffee, so the customer just receives the finished product.